@node bugs "Known bugs"
There are no real bugs known to the author.  Well, I use the program
everyday,  and  thereby I became my best beta-tester.  You shouldn't
come  across  severe  problems, like sudden meditations, even if you
try  to.   There might be some inconvieniences left, but the program
has been designed to be as riliable as possible.

DePack!   was  written,  compiled  and  linked  on  a Amiga 4000/040
platform  (Yeeeah...   that is speed).  It has been carefully tested
on  many  systens  without  showing  up any problems.  Of course the
author  can  give no guarantee for this program running on all Amiga
platforms  and  configurations with ROM version 37 or higher and the
required programs installed.

If you notice any bugs, or have problems with the program please send
a detailed bug report to the author.

See also : @{" Contacting the author " link contact}
@endnode



@node big "What are the differences between the demo and final version ??"
If  you  obtain the registerized version of the program, you'll will
receive a version with no restrictions left in it !  The loading and
saving  of  preferences  is enabled, and the program will try to get
your favourite settings on startup.

@endnode

@node keys "The magic is below your hands ..."
DePack!   is  controlled  by  keyboard  with  support  of  intuition
elements  like menus or file-requesters.  Nevertheless, this program
enables/requires you to use the keyboard in nearly every window.

Here is how the keys are assigned :

	Return/Enter	-	Mark Entry below cursor
	Cursor Up	-	Move cursor one line up
	Cursor Down	-	Move cursor one line down
	Numeric CrsrUp	-	Move cursor one line up
	Numeric CrsrDw	-	Move cursor one line down (u guessed it!)
	Shift+CrsrUp	-	Move cursor one page up
	Shift+CrsrDw	-	Move cursor one page down
	Shift+NumCrsrUp	-	Move cursor one page up
	Shift+NumCrsrDw	-	Move cursor one page down
	Numeric Home	-	Move cursor to line #1
	Numeric	End	-	Move cursor to last line
	Numeric PgUp	-	Move cursor one page up
	Numeric PgDw	-	Move cursor one page down
@endnode


@node tech "Technical information"
DePack!   opens  a  public  screen (name :  'DePack!.n'), so you can
open   any  other  program/window  with  public  screen  support  on
DePack!'s  screen.  (n is the count number.  Starting with _0_ it is
increased for every launched DePack!-program, e.g.  the 4th instance
of the program has the public screenname 'DePack!.3')

DePack!   in  todays form was developed in 18 months of more or less
intensive  work (10 months of intensive work, 8 were lazy business).
In the beginning a Amiga 500 with a 52MB harddisk and 4 MB of memory
(well  unaccelerated  ...  This is why I got used to call this stage
'the  stone age') was used and later I get hands on a Amiga 4000/40,
210  MB SCSI-hd and 12 MB of RAM:  (wow...  unfortunatly this is not
my  computer  ;-).   The  sourcecode  is split into 16 modules to be
linked after compilation and is ca.  210 KBytes long.

Below is information for all those freaks out there who want to know
more  about  the  coder-side  of  DePack!.  It features explanations
about the interesting stuff in the source-code and how some problems
have been solved.

@{b} Storing the dirfile @{ub}

The  dirfile  is read in one piece via dos.library's Read() command.
Then  the  carriage  returns  (ASCII  value  =  10) are converted to
C-string-terminators  (0).   An 32000-item pointer array (fixed size
[yet],  allocated  with AllocMem()) is used to store the pointers to
the  beginning  of  the  text  lines.  The dirfile struct looks like
this:

	struct DirFileData		/* Data of loaded dir-file */
		{
		int	lines;		/* # of lines */
		char **	linesbuffer;	/* Pointer to line-pointers */
		char *	dirbuf;		/* Pointer to beginning of dir-mem */
		int	dirsize;	/* Total size in bytes */
		int	begrange;	/* Start line of range */
		int	endrange;	/* End line of range */
		};


@{b} Searching @{ub}

Although  the  search  routine  seems  to be very fast no special or
complex   alogorithm   is   used.    Search   is  started  from  the
cursor-line±1.   The  loop value is increased until the start/end of
the  dirfile  is  encountered or a line contained the search string.
The  search-a-string-in-one-line  function  is very simple featuring
the C-standard function strnicmp() :

	BOOL SearchInLine (char * myline, char * str, int length)
	{
	int i,j
	BOOL notfound=TRUE;
	j = strlen (myline)-length;
	for (i=0;(notfound)&&(i<=j);i++)
		{
		notfound = strnicmp (myline+i,str,length);
			}
	return (!notfound);
	}


@{b} Scrolling and the Textdisplay @{ub}

The   text   of  the  current  dirfile  is  brought  on  screen  via
gfx.library's Text()-function.  The scrolling of the visible part of
a  window  is  done via ScrollRaster().  To my knowledge this is the
fastest  system-conform  way of scrolling without investing too much
time in writing custom blitter routines.  If you know better, please
let me know.


@{b} Windows and the Public Screen @{ub}

As  mentioned above DePack!  opens a public screen called DePack!.n.
The  console  windows  used for executing commands or the shells are
started  via  dos.library's  Open().   The  public  screen  name  is
embedded  in  the CON:...  specification via console.device's SCREEN
option (Yeah ...  OS>2.0 rulez!).


@{b} Determining the filetypes @{ub}

To determine the file type the first 300 bytes of the file are read.
Then  they  are  matched  against  patterns like 'DMS!' or 'ILBM' to
determine their type.  Texts are recognised by checking if more than
240  of  the  bytes are displayable ASCII-characters (The routine is
quite  simple, see the TERM or RSYS source code for a better one.  I
will  try to use the WhatIs or a similar library for the recognition
parts as soon as I get my hands on their docs and includes) :

	for (i=0;i<300;i++)
		{
		buffer [i] = fgetc (readfile);
		if ((buffer [i]>=32) && (buffer [i]<=127)) charcount++;
		}
	if ((strncmp (buffer,"DMS!",4)) == 0)   return (1);	/* dms */
		.
		.
		.
	if ((strncmp (buffer+8,"ILBM",4)) == 0) return (6);	/* pic *.
	if (charcount>240) return (4); 	/* possible Textfile recognised */

@endnode

@node dirfilestruct "The inner core"
Depack!   uses  several layout conventions of the @{"Dirfile" link terminology} which must
be obeyed when you load files for use as Depack!-directory-files.

· The maximum line length is currently 100 characters.
· The amount of total lines is limited to 32000

The @{"Dirfile" link terminology} is a textfile with the following structure :

	Entry 1
	Entry 2
	  ·
	  ·
	  ·
	Entry n




An entry is defined as :

	Startline
	Descriptionline 1
	Descriptionline 2
	  ·
	  ·
	  ·
	Descriptionline n



Startline :

<filename><white space><comment><carriage return>

filename	· valid AmigaOS-filename (limited to 30 characters)
<white space>	· space or tab character
<comment>	· optional description
carriage return · ASCII # 10





Descriptionline :
<white space><comment><carriage return>

white space	· space or tab character
comment 	· optional description
carriage return · ASCII # 10




Example of two valid entries :
------------------------------

PARTY93.DMS  P 110835  09-01-93  ·+­­­­­­!­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­+·
                                  |  _  _:____  ________________/\ [Hb]| 
                                  |      ˇ\ __\/_/ / __/_  / __/  \    | 
                                  |    _  _\ \/ / /___/ / / /\/ /\/    | 
                                  |     _/___/ /\__/_/\_\_\/\  /       | 
                                  |          \/              \/        | 
                                 ·+­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­­+·
                                  `   INVITATION  FOR  THE PARTY III   '
is a valid entry.


its_sm.dms                645771 ----rwed 05-Oct-93 17:27:25
jhh.lc!.txt                43613 ----rwed 05-Oct-93 17:55:48
JSM-NBA1.DMS              710036 ----rwed 17-Oct-93 22:16:59
JSM-NBA2.DMS              751952 ----rwed 17-Oct-93 22:10:33
JSM-NBA3.DMS              688716 ----rwed 17-Oct-93 22:09:42
JSM-NWBL.DMS              569952 ----rwed 17-Oct-93 22:32:21

is also valid. This is the output of a 'list' command




Example of invalid entry :
--------------------------

S_ST3.1.DMS  P 390871  09-01-93     __________ ______ ______ ________________
                                  _/  _____ I \\__ _ \\____ \\__ _____  ____/
                                  \___  \/     \/ _j  \/  |  \/  _>__\___  \ 
                                  /  !   \  T   \ l_   \  !   \  !~ \~  !   \
GREATPROGRAM                     /    ___/__l___/__l___/______/_____/___    /
                                 \____j-----------------------------sctl___/
                                      SHADESTRACKER 3.1 - LATEST UPDATE
                                                                   [-SlAyER-]

is  not  valid because the string "GREATPROGRAM" at the beginning of
the  5th  is  no  filename and deserves a <Space> or <Tab> appearing
before to belong to the description.

A @{"Dirfile" link terminology}  can  contain  many subsequent entries.  If you select an
item  by  pressing  <Return>  or  <Enter>  anywhere on the start- or
descriptionline belonging to the entry, it will get marked !

@endnode



@node easystart "Easy start ..."
Well,   I  included  a  textfile  on  the  disk  that  gives  you  a
tutorial-like   step-by-step  introduction  on  the  most  important
functions  of  DePack!  You'll find it in the Main drawer its called
@{" EasyStart.txt " link DePack!:EasyStart.txt/main"}

@endnode



@node about "About DePack!"
DePack! is an easy-to-use tool for /X sysops and traders who like to
DePack! their software stored and cramped into packed files produced
by archivers like 'lha', 'zoo', diskmashed with 'dms' or simply read
the newest textfiles available in their software-directories.

The  basic  idea  is  that  you  select a couple of files from an /X
directory  simply  by  marking  them  with a cursor and then perform
certain  operations  e.g.   copy  them to an other directory, delete
them  or  (and  that is the main thing behind DePack!) call external
commands  (in  form  of  AmigaDos executables) depending on the file
type.   This  means that e.g.  if you select an DiskMasher-file, you
are  asked to enter a disk and then the 'dms'-command will be called
externally  and  the  data stored in the .dms-file will be written a
disk  in  df0:.   If  the  file  is  a IFF-ILBM file you can call an
external viewer and display the picture stored in the file.

This  whole  idea was born by some member(s) of the group 'D-TECT' a
long  time  ago.  They released 'D-Tect's Deluxe DePacker', but this
programm was so badly written (assembler hardcode) with so many bugs
and  a  bad GUI that I decided to reprogram the whole thing with the
following goals in my mind :  a) Written in C (as I started coding C
last  year)  b)  High-Quality  Graphical  User Interface c) Enhanced
functions and features.
@endnode

@node install "Installing DePack!"
To  install  DePack!   double click the Icon 'DePack!-Install'.  You
must   have   the   commodore   installer  tool  installed  in  your
c:-directory.  Once started, the installation procedure is completly
self-explanatory.  Simply following the on-screen instructions.

See Also : 

@{" Requirements " link requirements}
@endnode

@node requirements "Requirements"
DePack!   needs  some  additional  files to pop up, some of them are
essential to start the program, some of them are optional :

Required things :

- Operating System 2.04 or higher (starting with V37.175)
			- for the GadTools.library GUI
			  and several other new features not
			  available under V1.2 or V1.3

- diskfont.library (V37 or higher)
			- for the output routines.
			  You can find this library in the
			  libs directory of the Workbench disk
			  that came with your computer.

- reqtools.library (V38 or higher)
			- for the various requesters.
			  You can find this library in many
			  PD-packages. It's not included here
			  for copyright reasons.


Optional things :

- amigaguide.library (any version will do)
			- for using the hypertext-help system
			  You can find this library in the
			  libs directory of the Workbench (V2.1+)
			  disk that came with your computer. Note :

- fonts:p0t-noodle.font - If this font is present DePack! will use it
  fonts:p0t-noodle/8	  as the default 8bit-monospace-font

@endnode

@node starterrors "Error's while starting DePack!"
When  trying  to  start DePack, it probably prints out several error
codes  if  it  has  some  problems  while  finding free libraries or
memories.   Look  into  the list below how to find and fix the error
codes.

	@{" Error  1 " link error1}  Error opening disk libraries
	@{" Error  2 " link error2}  Error opening ROM libraries
	@{" Error  3 " link error3}  Error opening screen
	@{" Error  4 " link error4}  Error opening window
@endnode

@node error1 "Error 1 while starting DePack!"
DePack!   had  problems opening the required libraries.  Perhaps you
need a newer version of a library or the library is not installed in
the libs:  drawer

	Libraries Required		Versions Required/

	diskfont.library		>=V37
	reqtools.library		>=V38
@endnode

@node error2 "Error 2 while starting DePack!"
DePack!   had  problems opening the required ROM libraries.  Perhaps
you  have  a wrong kickstart (V1.3 or lower).  DePack!  only runs on
V2.0 or a newer version of the operating system :

	Libraries Required		Versions Required

	gadtools.library		>=V37
	intuition.library		>=V37
	gfx.library			>=V37
@endnode

@node error3 "Error 3 opening screen"
DePack!  had problems opening the screen.  Perhaps you have too less
chip memory free. Close other applications and try again.
@endnode

@node error4 "Error 4 opening window"
DePack!  had problems opening the window.  Perhaps you have too less
chip memory free. Close other applications and try again.
@endnode

@node localising "Localising DePack!"
The  newest  versions  of  DePack!  starting with V39 are localised,
this  means  that  you  can  interact  with the program in different
languages  of your preference.  Currently there are only 2 languages
included  :   English  (default)  and German.  This poor variety has
three  reasons  :   a)  I  included  the  language files in the main
program, and they take up to 30kb per language b) I can neither read
nor write in any other languages and c) I don't think the program is
not  so  well-spread  to  justify such a big work as writing catalog
files for Polish or Greek users.

Localising the program is very simple.  If you haven't installed the
program  yet,  use  the  supplied  installer  script  to install the
program with the language of your preference.

If  you  have  already  installed  the  program,  you  can  create a
localised  version very simply.  You don't need locale.libary or any
catalog  files.   The localised strings are all included in the main
program.   You  just  have  to  tell DePack!  that you want to use a
different  language.

Do so by issuing the following command lines :

1> echo >envarc:depack!/langauge "<Name of the language>"
1> echo >env:depack!/langauge "<Name of the language>"

If  you  get a message like "echo:  unable to open redirection file"
you  propably haven't created the envarc:depack!  directory yet.  In
this case create one with the following :

1> makedir envarc:depack!
1> makedir env:depack!

and  retry the commands above.  If you have still problems, leave me
a  note with a _detailled_ description of your steps and I'll try to
help you.

@endnode

