@node aboutprefs "About the preferences"
DePack!   can be configured via several preferences.  They allow the
user  to  change  the  program's broad variety of settings e.g.  the
needed  paths  or if you want DePack!  to react on diskchange-events
while depacking the files.

The  preferences  can be changed by using the program's menus or the
preferences window :

Preferences window :

	@{" Edit Preferences " link iprefs} pops up the main prefs window
	@{" Mode             " link mprefs} controls mode of processing

	@{" Reset to last saved ..." link rprefs} resets the settings
	@{" Load             " link lprefs} loads new settings from disk
	@{" Save             " link sprefs} saves current settings as defaults
	@{" Save as          " link aprefs} saves current settings in file

You  can  save  those  settings like normal AmigaDos-preferences and
load them in an later session.  On startup DePack!  tries to use the
preferences stored in a the file 'env:DePack:DePack!.prefs'.  If its
not  there  the  program  switches  back  to  its  internal  default
settings.

@endnode

@node iprefs "Global Preferences"
A  window  with  many  string  gadgets  in it will pop up :  you can
change  the  preferences  here.   To understand this you should have
read  the introduction to the @{"'DePack!-process'" link m_depack} before.

The  first  nine  boxes  on the left side build the interface to the
external  commands.   They will be used as follows:  If you selected
the  menu-item @{" Mode/DePack!  " link mprefs} .  DePack!  analyses
the  files  in  the  source-directories and tries to determine their
type.   In  95%  of all cases they can be recognised as 'DMS','LHa',
...  (all the other files that can't be matched need to be specified
by  you).   Here,  by  means  of  the interface preferences, you can
determine  in which way, the recognised files file are treated.  For
every file an external command according to your preferences will be
called.   So  you  have  to  enter  the commandlines (the ones you'd
normally  enter in the CLI/Shell) and replace the source name by %s,
and  the  destination  name  by  %d.   For example if the CLI normal
commandline you'd normally use from the Shell would look like this :

	c:dms write bbs:conf1/upload/test.dms drive=df0:

the corresponding line in the preferences would be :

	c:dms write %s drive=%d

The letters %s and %d will be replaced by the correct paths later on
(see below).

In  the  three  uppermost  boxes  on  the  right  side  you have the
possibility  to  enter  one or more source-directories.  By entering
valid  AmigaOS-paths you tell the program where to find the files to
be processed.  DePack!  will scan them in the order 1, 2, 3.  NOTE :
If  one  of  the gadgets contains no string it will be considered as
the  current directory.  This can be a little bit confusing when you
scan for files not denoted (See also :  @{" Files not denoted " link m_notden}.
So  you better set unneeded source-directory strings to NIL:

The  box  below  contains  the  destination  directory.  The %d (see
above) is going to be replaced by this string or, if you are in copy
mode,  the  files  will  be  copied  to  this destination-directory.
Warning  :   If  you use the directory-requester for this gadget and
select  e.g.   df0:   in the DirReq-window the reqtools.library will
return the name of the disk instead of df0:  (example Empty:).  This
can  be  fatal  if  you need to change the disks in DePack!  or copy
mode.   So  if  you got to enter a DEVICE-name use the string gadget
and NOT the 'Get' button.

The next string gadget determines the /X-directory file to be worked
on.   If  select  a  new  file,  it will be loaded after closing the
window with the close-gadget. It is also possible to enter only the
name of a valid AmigaOS directory.

The  last  5  gadgets  discussed  above  can be easily operated by a
file-requester  if  you  press  the  button labled 'Get' next to the
boxes.

If  the  first  on/off-gadget called 'Detect Diskchange' is selected
DePack!        will       detect      diskchanges      when      the
'Process|...|Skip|Abort'-requester    is    on   screen   and   will
automagically  satisfy the requester if a disk is inserted in one of
the  drives.   (Be  careful  !  This feature doesn't know about your
destination ...  this can cause unwanted writes in certain cases but
normally there should be no problem with this option.)

The  one  labeled  'Skip  Unknown'  tells  DePack!   how to react on
unknown  filetypes.   If  it  is selected the program will skip this
ones  otherwise you will be asked to determine the file by yourself.

The  third  gadget  labeled  'Fast  Reqs' increases the speed of the
progress  displays  (causing a loss of precision on the other hand).
Might be useful on slow machines.

When the last one named 'Immediate Start' is selected the processing
of the files will start immediatly after you selected the menu item,
so  you  needn't  to  press the 'Start/Stop'-gadget.  You don't need
this  option,  but  it  becomes  quit handy if you scan through some
textfiles etc. by selecting only one file a time.

@endnode

@node mprefs "Modes of operation"
DePack! can operate in four different modes :


@{b}Mode		Function@{ub}

DePack		Uses external commands like lha etc. for unpacking
		the sourcefiles.

Copy		Copies the selected files to the destination directory

Smart Copy	Copies the selected files to the destination directory
		and arranges the order so that multiple destination
		disks are filled as best as possible (Use this on
		devices that support diskchange like df0: or a
		SyQuest® drive)

Delete		Deletes the stuff from the source directories
@endnode

@node rprefs "Resetting the preferences"
If  you  have  changed  the preferences this will undo your changes.
The  preferences  will be set to the state they had at the last time
you saved them, or, if you haven't saved them, to the preferences on
program startup.

@endnode

@node lprefs "Load Preferences"
A  file  requester  pops  up  and  you can choose a previously saved
DePack!-preferences  file to load.  If you have selected entries you
need  to  confirm  that  you  are  willing to load the new prefs and
thereby a new AmiX-directory file

@{b}!!! MENU ONLY PRESENT IN REGISTERED VERSION !!!@{ub}
@endnode

@node sprefs "Save Preferences as default"
Save  the  preferences  from  the  preferences  window  to  the file
'ENVARC:DePack!/DePack!.prefs'.   This is the file DePack!  tries to
open  on startup - If it's found and valid, the program will use the
settings stored in there.

@{b}!!! MENU ONLY PRESENT IN REGISTERED VERSION !!!@{ub}
@endnode

@node aprefs "Save Preferences into file"
A  file  requester  pops up and you are asked to enter the name of a
file  in  which  the actual preferences will be saved.  You can load
this  file  in  a  later  session with the Preferences/@{"Load" link lprefs}
command.   WARNING  :   This  will  only  save  the  contents of the
preferences window!  Any file selection of yours won't be saved!

@{b}!!! MENU ONLY PRESENT IN REGISTERED VERSION !!!@{ub}
@endnode

@node menus "The DePack! menus - ĺ la carte"

	@{b}Project@{ub}

		@{" Load dirfile ... " link m_dirload} open @{"Dirfile" link terminology}
		@{" Save dirfile " link m_dirsave} save @{"Dirfile" link terminology} over old file
		@{" Save dirfile as... " link m_dirsaveas} save @{"Dirfile" link terminology} with new name
		@{" Reload dirfile " link m_dirreload} restore @{"Dirfile" link terminology} from disk
		@{" Read directory ..." link m_dirread} convert a directory into a @{"Dirfile" link terminology}
		@{" About " link m_stupido} displays information on the program
		@{" Version " link m_stupido} displays additional information
		@{" Sleep ... " link m_sleep} in case you get tired ...
		@{" Quit " link m_quit} quits out


	@{b}Preferences@{ub}

		@{" Edit Preferences " link iprefs} edit interface settings 
		@{" Mode " link mprefs} determines mode of processing
			DePack
			Copy
			Smart Copy
			Delete
		@{" Screenmode ..." link m_screenmode} select display mode for DePack!-screen
		@{" Font ... " link m_font} select font for dirfile display
		@{" Reset to last saved ..." link rprefs} resets the settings
		@{" Load ... " link lprefs} loads new settings from disk
		@{" Save " link sprefs} saves settings as default
		@{" Save as... " link aprefs} saves new settings to file


	@{b}DePack!@{ub}

		@{" DePack! " link m_depack} start processing
		@{" Untag items " link m_deletelist} unselects marked entries
		Mark Range
			@{" Beginning " link m_markstart} marks begin of Range
			@{" End " link m_markend} marks end of Range
		@{" Tag items in range " link m_tagrange} Select Files in range
		@{" Clear range " link m_clearrange} Remove Range
		@{" Load tags... " link m_loadtags} Restore tags from disk
		@{" Save tags... " link m_savetags} Save tags to disk


	@{b}Dirfile@{ub}

		Search
			@{" forwards " link m_search} search for a custom string from top of dir
			@{" backwards " link m_search} search for a custom string from bottom of dir
		Continue Search
			@{" forwards " link m_csearch} search for a custom string from top of dir
			@{" backwards " link m_csearch} search for a custom string from bottom of dir
		@{" Enter highlight pattern " link m_highlon} highlight lines according to pattern
		@{" Turn highlight off " link m_highloff} turn highlighting off
		@{" Jump to entry " link m_jumpentry} move cursor to a selected item
		@{" Jump to line " link m_jumpline} move cursor to a certain line
		@{" Filter not existing files " link m_filter} modify @{"Dirfile" link terminology} to show only present files
		@{" Filter existing files " link m_filterex} modify @{"Dirfile" link terminology} to show only NOT present files
		@{" Show not denoted files " link m_notden} show files on HD but not in @{"Dirfile" link terminology}
		@{" Strip empty lines " link m_removeempty} removes unused lines from Dirfile
		@{" Strip equal lines " link m_removeequal} removes double lines from Dirfile


	@{b}Information@{ub}

		@{" About the Help system " link m_abouthelp} in case you get lost ...
		@{" Key index " link m_keyindex}
		Help
			@{" General information " link m_generalhelp} General AmigaGuide help
			@{" Help on menus " link m_menuhelp} Menu explanation (AmigaGuide)
			@{" Program History " link m_historyhelp} What's new ? (AmigaGuide)
			@{" Copyrights " link m_copyrhelp} Legal stuff (AmigaGuide)
		@{" Display Info " link m_displayinfo} some technical/debugging infos


	@{b}Extras@{ub}

		@{" Register/Update ..." link m_regupdate} print out a registration/update document
		@{" Format a disk ..." link m_formatadisk} call systems format command
		@{" Open Shell window ... " link m_newshell} opens a shell on the DePack!-screen
		@{" Install No Virus Bootblock " link m_vbb} installs a viruskiller-bootblock ;-]

@endnode

@node m_stupido "????????????????"
You don't tell me you need help on an about requester, eh ???
@endnode


@node m_dirload "Load Dirfile"
This  function  loads  a @{"Dirfile" link terminology}.  Eventually marked entries will be
discarded  after  a confirmation requester.  This functions performs
the  same  operations  as  if  you  would  change the dirname in the
preferences requester.
@endnode

@node m_dirsave "Save Dirfile"
This  function  saves current @{"Dirfile" link terminology} over the old dirfile.
@endnode

@node m_dirsaveas "Save Dirfile as..."
This  function  saves current @{"Dirfile" link terminology} to a file you specify.
@endnode

@node m_dirreload "Reload Dirfile"
This  function  restores  the dirfile from disk into memory.  May be useful
after filter operations to undo changes.
@endnode

@node m_dirread "Create Dirfile"
This  routine  scans  a  directory  of  your  choice  and  builds  a
pseudo-@{"Dirfile" link terminology} from it.  Here is an example :

Filename		 Size	Filecomment

dir			 1233	Dir-Command
list			 2933	List-Command
test			38882	Text-file

On  selecting  the  menu item you are asked to determine a directory
via  the  dir-requester.   Afterward  you  can  enter  a pattern the
filenames  must match.  Example (#?.dms or #?amix#?) The dir will be
read  and  if  you  want  (and  you usually want to) you can add the
directory  to  the  search-path  list afterwards (It won't overwrite
your  path  settings.   An  invisible 4th source-directory-string is
used).
@endnode

@node m_sleep "Sleep ... zzzzzz"
Selecting  this  item  will  put the program to sleep i.e.  the main
screen  is  closed  and  a  small  window will appear on the default
public screen.  After selecting the menu item you have the choice of
puttting  the  program  into  a  small  window on the default public
screen  or  to  put the program into the tools menu of the Workbench
(this  is  of  course  only possible if the WB is open).  Close this
window   to  reopen  DePack!.   Don't  worry  :   The  dirfile,  all
modifications,  the  tagged  items  and  the  preferences  won't  be
changed.

@endnode


@node m_quit "Quitting DePack!"
If  you  select  this  entry  you are about to leave the program (oh
no!).   If  there are still files to tagged or preferences not saved
you will be warned.

@endnode

@node m_depack "Processing the files"
A  window  will  open  with  three @{"Listview" link terminology} gadgets and other useful
infos  at  the top.  All files you marked will be listed in the left
@{"Listview" link terminology}  gadget.  You can use the slider to scroll the list(s).  To
start  processing  press  the 'Start/Stop'-Gadget' (left side at the
bottom)  If  you  want  to  return  to the main window use the other
button called 'Close Window'.


@{b} Mode : DePack! @{ub}

All the entries in the @{"Dirfile" link terminology} selected by the user will be searched
in  the  three directories you specified in the @{"Preferences" link iprefs} section.
If they are found they will be interrogated and the program tries to
determine  their  type.  If DePack!  can't recognise the filetype of
the file currently processed, you as the user will have to enter the
type  manually  by satisfying the requester popping up with choosing
Option  '1'  up to '9' and thereby selecting the file-type, pressing
skip  to  process  the  next  file,  or  abort  to  cancel the whole
operation.  If the filetype has been determined (see chart below for
the  numbers  and  their  meaning  ...)  you have four options :  a)
process  the  file and call the according command you entered in the
@{"Preferences" link iprefs}  window  b) to skip the file and process the next one in
the  list  c)  to  re-process  the  last  file (without dropping the
current  file  of  course  !)  d) change the type of treatment (this
might  be  of  some  use  in certain cases) or to e) Abort the whole
operation.   If you selected a) Process an output window will pop up
and  your  commandline  will  be  called with the output send to the
mentioned window.  This whole process is looped until the whole list
of files has been processed or you selected abort.  In either of the
case  you  have  the  option  to untag your selections afterwards by
reaction on another requester.

The  current  file's  description  will be displayed in the @{"Listview" link terminology}
gadget  called  'Current  File'.  After processing a file the result
(e.g.   'File  X copied' or 'File X not found') will be added to the
@{"Listview" link terminology} entitled 'Results'.


@{b} Mode : Copy @{ub}

This mode will copy all files to the selected destination directory.
If  the destination-device is full you are asked to enter a new disk
or  to  format  a disk.  This will bring up a string requester, that
will ask you to enter a format commandline like you would use in the
shell.   (e.g.  format device=rad:  name=stuff).  This line is saved
with  the preferences and will not change until you modify it in the
string  gadget. 
You can abort copying by pressing the start/stop gadget.

NOTE  :  Use this copy-mode for Harddisk to Harddisk copying (or any
other  device  that  offers  enough  space to hold all files without
disk-changing).   If you need multiple destination disks to hold all
files use Smart copy (see below) instead.


@{b} Mode : Smart Copy @{ub}

This mode will copy all files to the selected destination directory.
The  order  in  which the files are copied is arranged in a way that
the  files  are  copied in a way that the multiple destination disks
are  filled  best, so  that  you save disks.  Example :  Imagine you
would  like  to  copy the following files to df0:  (which has a free
size of approx.  850000 bytes if you use blank Old filesystem disks)

FILE1		Size : 810000 bytes
FILE2		Size : 830000 bytes
FILE3		Size : 30000  bytes

The 'normal' copy (intended for Harddisk to Harddisk copying) would
do the following

·	Copy file1 to df0: (1st disk)
·	Ask for next disk
·	Copy file2 to df0: (2nd disk)
·	Ask for next disk
·	Copy file3 to df0: (3rd disk)

Smart copy does the following :

·	Copy file2 to df0: (1st disk)
·	Ask for next disk
·	Copy file2 to df0: (2nd disk)
·	Copy file3 to df0: (2nd disk)

Thereby you saved 1 disk.



@{b} Mode : Delete @{ub}

After  two  confirmation  requesters  this  function will delete all
files  that  were  found.   You  can abort this mode by pressing the
start/stop gadget.

When  all files have been processed you can look at the results etc.
or  press  the  'Close  Window' button to return to the main window.
@endnode

@node m_deletelist "Untag items"
Deletes all the file-selections you made (not the files themselves).
You  have  to  satisfy  to  'Are u sure ?'-requesters to confirm the
actions.
@endnode

@node m_screenmode "Select screenmode"
This  opens  a  screenmode  requester and you can select a different
screenmode for the DePack!  screen.  The screen information is saved
with the preferences file

@endnode

@node m_font "Select dirfile font"
This  opens  a for requester and you can select a _non-proportional_
font  for  the  dirfile display.  The font information is saved with
the  preferences  file.   To  change  the font used in the menus and
requesters  use  the  OS'  font  preferences  program and change the
default Screen Text.

@endnode

@node m_markstart "Mark start of range"
The current line will be considered as the start of a range.  If you
have  previously  selected the end of the range, it will get visible
by turning into a different colour.

@endnode

@node m_markend "Mark end of range"
The  current  line will be considered as the end of a range.  If you
have previously selected the start of the range, it will get visible
by turning into a different colour.

@endnode

@node m_tagrange "Tag files in Range"
This  function  will  tag  all  filenames  it  encounters within the
previously  selected  range.   Those files can be processed with the
DePack!  option.

@endnode

@node m_clearrange "Clear range"
The  previously  selected range will be cleared, i.e.  the start and
endlines will be reset, and the textdisplay turns normal again.  The
dirfile won't get modified by this operation.

@endnode


@node m_loadtags "Restore tags from disk"
With  the  help  of this function you are able to restore previously
saved  tags from disk.  Select the file with the requester and there
you are ...

@endnode

@node m_savetags "Markierungen laden"
This function will save the tags to a file you specify.  Thereby you
can  load  them  later  in  a different session, to reuse them (e.g.
after a reset).

@endnode

@node m_removeempty "Remove empty lines"
You'll often find a lot of empty lines in a dirfile.  This function
strips them away.

@endnode

@node m_removeequal "Remove equal lines"
Sometimes  one  lines  can  be  found many times in the same Dirfile
(maybe  the  advertisment from a trader/group etc.).  This functions
reads  the  line  under  the cursor, and scans the Dirfile for equal
lines.  Those will get stripped.  This function deletes at least one
line from the dirfile, i.e.  the line under the cursor.

@endnode

@node m_search "Search for string forwards/backwards"
You are asked to enter a string to be searched for.  The search will
be started from the current cursor position.

@endnode

@node m_csearch "Continue search for string forwards/backwards"
Continues to search for the string @{"you entered before" link m_search} (from the current
cursor position in the lower (forwards) or upper (backwards) direction.
@endnode

@node m_highlon "Turn highlight on"
This  function  highlights  every  line  that  contains a string you
entered   before.   This  is  very  useful  if  you  e.g.   want  to
concentrate  on  .dms-files  :   You  enter  :  '.dms' at the string
requester  and every line that contains '.dms' (which is used in the
filename) gets highlighted.
@endnode

@node m_highloff "Turn highlight off"
Well  ...   erm  ...  this turns highlighting off ...  Any questions
left ?
@endnode

@node m_jumpline "Jump to line"
This  function  asks  you  for  a  line number and then postions the
cursor on that line.
@endnode

@node m_jumpentry "Jump to entry"
This  function  asks  you  for an entry number and then postions the
cursor on that line with the entry number.
@endnode

@node m_filter "Filter non existant files"
This  function  will  scan  the three source directories for all the
filenames  in  the  @{"Dirfile" link terminology} and then remove all the entries from the
directory  that  are not present in the source-directories.  This is
useful  if  you  got  many  files not present and don't want them to
appear  in the directory-display.  You can save the @{"Dirfile" link terminology} with the
@{"Save dirfile" link m_dirsave} menu item.
@endnode

@node m_filterex "Filter existant files"
This  functions  does  nearly  the same as @{"Filter non existant files" link m_filter}
exept   that   it   will   only  leave  files  NOT  present  in  the
source-directories in the @{"Dirfile" link terminology}.
@endnode

@node m_notden "Show not denoted files"
This  function  will  scan the three sourcedirectories for any files
not  denoted  in  the  @{"Dirfile" link terminology}  and  will  display  a  list  of them
afterwards.
@endnode

@node m_keyindex "Key index"
This opens a requester displaying the key-controls of the program.

See also :

@{" Key index " link keys}
@endnode

@node m_abouthelp "About the help system"
Displays  some requesters informing you about the help-system of the
program.

@endnode

@node m_generalhelp "General help"
This  item  provides  this hypertext-document on the DePack!-screen.
This  functions  requires  amigaguide-library  present in your libs:
directory.

@endnode

@node m_menuhelp "Help on menu system"
This  item  provides  a  hypertext-document  on  the  DePack!-screen
providing  information about the menus.  You can also move the mouse
pointer  over  a  menu (sub-) item and press <HELP>.  @{b}This functions
requires amigaguide-library present in your libs:  directory.@{ub}

@endnode

@node m_historyhelp "What's new ?"
This  item  provides  a  hypertext-document  on  the  DePack!-screen
telling  you  more about the history of the program.  @{b}This functions
requires   amigaguide-library  present  in  your  libs:   directory.@{ub}

@endnode

@node m_copyrhelp "Legal stuff"
This   item   provides   displays   a   hypertext-document   on  the
DePack!-screen  giving information on the copyright situation.@{b}  This
functions   requires   amigaguide-library   present  in  your  libs:
directory.@{ub}
@endnode

@node m_displayinfo
Displays  some  information about screen and window sizes etc.  Used
mainly for debugging purposes, so you don't really need this item.

@endnode

@node m_regupdate "Registration/Update..."
Opens a requester, that gives you the possibility to enter you name,
address etc.  and then to print out a registration/update form.  You
can  send  this  document  to  the  author  and will get the current
version of the program in exchange.

@endnode

@node m_formatadisk "Formatting a disk"
On  selecting  this item you will be asked to enter a command string
that  calls  your format utility (e.g.  "format device=rad:  quick")
exactly  as  you would do in the shell.  The string you entered here
will be saved with the preferences for later use.

@endnode

@node m_newshell "Open a shell window on the DePack! screen"
This  opens  a shell window on the screen.  The program will be in a
waiting state until you close the shell with 'EndShell', 'EndCli' or
by clicking the closebox of the window.

@endnode

@node m_vbb "Well discover yourself"
A very @{b}useful@{ub} option (eerm) !

@endnode


@node shareware "A word on shareware and public-domain"
I   spent   a   lot   of   time  wondring  whether  to  release  the
DePack!-package as freeware/shareware a commercial product, or maybe
something  between.   I  know many shareware-authors in germany, who
got  very  little or even no response on their programs, even if the
software  they  produced was high-quality stuff worth much more than
they were demanding.

I spent approximately ...  well many (too much ?) months on DePack!,
a  time  in  which  I learned a lot about C-programming as well as a
whole  lotta  more  about  the traps and back-doors of C-programming
;-).   So I think the best way that matches my efforts is to release
a  DePack!-evalution version, so that you can check out the facility
the  program  offers  you  and give you the possibility to order the
complete  DePack!-package  for  20  DM  (Germany)  or 20$ (all other
countries).

The complete DePack!-package consists of :

         DePack! - full working version with no restraints
       1 free update (will be mailed to you when you want to)

So do not hesitate ... @{"register" link contact}@{b} NOW @{ub}!
@endnode

